While developing a Bitbucket add-on I noticed the {{user}} [lifecycle attribute|https://developer.atlassian.com/bitbucket/descriptor/lifecycle.html] sent to my add-on on installation is the same as the {{principal}} attribute even though I installed the add-on for a team, as a user (that is part of said team).

I.e, I get:

{code}
{
	"productType": "bitbucket",
	"principal": {
		"username": "productize",
		"website": "https://productize.be/",
		"display_name": "productize",
		"uuid": "{8d07dd4d-...
		"type": "team"
	},
	"user": {
		"username": "productize",
		...
		"uuid": "{8d07dd4d-...
		"type": "team"
	},
    ...
}
{code}

While I would expect something like:

{code}
{
	"productType": "bitbucket",
	"principal": {
		"username": "productize",
		"website": "https://productize.be/",
		"display_name": "productize",
		"uuid": "{8d07dd4d- ...
		"type": "team",
		...
	},
	"user": {
		"username": "seppestas",
		"website": "https://sep.pe/",
		"display_name": "seppestas",
		"type": "user",
		...
	},
	...
}
{code}

Which would be a lot more useful for e.g security auditing purposes.

In order to keep even relatively simple pipelines configurations DRY, we are required to write scripts referenced by pipelines.  What I *can* do is use [YAML anchors|http://www.yaml.org/spec/1.2/spec.html#id2785586] to reference an entire pipeline:

{code:yaml}
image: node
pipelines:
  custom:
    run-tests: &run-tests
      - step:
          script:
            - npm install
            - node_modules/.bin/grunt eslint sasslint karma
  default: *run-tests
{code}

What I can&#x27;t do is compose multiple scripts.  For example, say I want several things to be custom scripts (so I can trigger them) and also compose them into branch scripts run automatically.  Because of the way that YAML anchors and inheritance/merging works, this:

{code:yaml}
image: node
pipelines:
  custom:
    run-tests:
      - step:
          script: &run-tests-script
            - npm install && export NPM_INSTALLED=1
            - node_modules/.bin/grunt eslint sasslint karma
    deploy-dev:
      - step:
          script: &deploy-dev-script
            - "[[ -n $NPM_INSTALLED ]] || npm install"
            - node_modules/.bin/grunt deploy:dev
    deploy-qa:
      - step:
          script: &deploy-qa-script
            - "[[ -n $NPM_INSTALLED ]] || npm install"
            - node_modules/.bin/grunt deploy:qa
  branches:
    master:
      - step:
          script:
            - *run-tests-script
            - *deploy-dev-script
            - *deploy-qa-script
{code}

Is parsed into this:

{code:javascript}
{
  "image": "node",
  "pipelines": {
    "custom": {
      "run-tests": [
        {
          "step": {
            "script": [
              "npm install && export NPM_INSTALLED=1",
              "node_modules/.bin/grunt eslint sasslint karma e2e"
            ]
          }
        }
      ],
      "deploy-dev": [
        {
          "step": {
            "script": [
              "[[ -n $NPM_INSTALLED ]] || npm install",
              "node_modules/.bin/grunt deploy:dev"
            ]
          }
        }
      ],
      "deploy-qa": [
        {
          "step": {
            "script": [
              "[[ -n $NPM_INSTALLED ]] || npm install",
              "node_modules/.bin/grunt deploy:qa"
            ]
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    "default": [
      {
        "step": {
          "script": [
            [
              "npm install && export NPM_INSTALLED=1",
              "node_modules/.bin/grunt eslint sasslint karma e2e"
            ],
            [
              "[[ -n $NPM_INSTALLED ]] || npm install",
              "node_modules/.bin/grunt deploy:dev"
            ],
            [
              "[[ -n $NPM_INSTALLED ]] || npm install",
              "node_modules/.bin/grunt deploy:qa"
            ]
          ]
        }
      }
    ]
  }
}
{code}

The offending piece being the array of arrays of strings in {{script}}.  By flattening arrays of arrays of strings in {{script}} you would allow further customization of pipelines.

An alternative to this would be to simply allow multiple steps as those can be composed purely in YAML.

Disabling notifications in account settings also blocks receiving transfer requests, and the "initiator" of the transfer is left wondering why nothing is happening.

If notifications are disabled, the settings page says this:

{code}
#!python

Currently you only receive password reset and important account information by email.
{code}

I think transfer requests should be classified as "important account information", and _not_ affected by notification settings (I feel notification settings are mostly to prevent spamming, but these shouldn&#x27;t count).
